                <fr:title text="Affine commutation">Affine commutation</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/schm-86OJ/" title="Scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-86OJ/" display-uri="schm-86OJ" type="local">scheme</fr:link> and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link href="/schm-C6GR/" title="Affine local properties" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-C6GR/" display-uri="schm-C6GR" type="local">affine local</fr:link> property on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. If there exists an affine open cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{\operatorname {Spec} A_i\}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> with each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, then any affine open of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  Suppose we have an arbitrary affine open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> is quasi-compact, we can cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> by finitely many <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> with each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>. Since standard opens of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> form a basis, we can choose a generating family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{d_j\}_{j\in  J}]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigvee _{j\in  J}d_j = 1]]></fr:tex>, and each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/d_j]]></fr:tex> is contained in some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex>. But since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/d_j]]></fr:tex> is open compact in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex>, it can be identified as some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A_i/a_j]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_j]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i]]></fr:tex>. By assumption of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> being affine local, each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D/d_i]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
  The affine commutation lemma has a wide range of applications, because we can view properties of morphisms of schemes and sheaves on schemes as affine local properties:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
