            <fr:title text="Being Heyting/Boolean is affine local">Being Heyting/Boolean is affine local</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  The property of an affine open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec} A]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a <html:em>Heyting algebra</html:em> or a <html:em>Boolean algebra</html:em> is <fr:link href="/schm-C6GR/" title="Affine local properties" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-C6GR/" display-uri="schm-C6GR" type="local">affine local</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p> Evidently if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a Heyting algebra then so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/a]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p> 

  <html:p>
    Now suppose we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigvee _{i\in  I}a_i = 1]]></fr:tex> with each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i := A/a_i]]></fr:tex> a Heyting algebra. We will write abbreviate the localisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \twoheadrightarrow  A/a_i]]></fr:tex> simply as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-)_i := a_i \wedge  (-)]]></fr:tex>. For any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y \in  A]]></fr:tex>, we define
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \to  y := \bigvee _{i\in  I} x_i \to _i y_i, ]]></fr:tex>
    where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\to _i]]></fr:tex> is the Heyting implication in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i]]></fr:tex>. This is evidently monotone on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>. Hence, to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \to  (-)]]></fr:tex> is the right adjoint of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \wedge  -]]></fr:tex>, it suffices to give the unit and counit. 
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y\in  A]]></fr:tex>, the counit requires
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \wedge  (x \to  y) \le  y. ]]></fr:tex>
    Notice that by construction,
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x_i \to _i y_i \le  a_i. ]]></fr:tex>
    This way, using the counit of each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\to _i]]></fr:tex>, we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ 
      \begin {align*}
        x \wedge  (x_i \to _i y_i) 
        &= x \wedge  a_i \wedge  (x_i \to _i y_i) \\
        &= x_i \wedge  (x_i \to _i y_i) \\
        &\le  x_i \wedge  y_i
      \end {align*}
    ]]></fr:tex>
    It follows that
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ x \wedge  (x \to  y) = \bigvee _{i\in  I} x \wedge  (x_i \to _i y_i) \le  \bigvee _{i\in  I}x_i \wedge  y_i \le  y. ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
  <html:p>
    For the unit, it requires
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[ y \le  x \to  (x \wedge  y). ]]></fr:tex>
    By construction, using the unit for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\to _i]]></fr:tex>, we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
      \begin {align*}
        y 
        &= \bigvee _{i\in  I} y_i \\ 
        &\le  \bigvee _{i\in  I} x_i \to _i (x_i \wedge  y_i) \\ 
        &= x \to  (x \wedge  y)
      \end {align*}
    ]]></fr:tex></html:p>
  <html:p>
    The case for Boolean algebras is trivial.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
